.TH PORTCHECK 1 "February 2026" "portcheck 0.1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
portcheck \- check and kill processes by port
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B portcheck
\fIPORT\fR
[\fB\-\-kill\fR|\fB\-k\fR]
.br
.B portcheck
\fB\-\-list\fR
[\fB\-\-all\fR]
.br
.B portcheck
[\fB\-h\fR|\fB\-\-help\fR|\fB\-v\fR|\fB\-\-version\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B portcheck
shows which process is using a given port, and optionally kills it.
It uses
.BR lsof (1)
to query open connections.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \fIPORT\fR
Show the process using the specified port number (1\(en65535).
.TP
.B \fIPORT\fR \-\-kill
Kill the process using the port after interactive confirmation.
.TP
.B \fIPORT\fR \-k
Kill the process immediately without confirmation.
.TP
.B \-\-list, \-l
List all ports currently in LISTEN state.
.TP
.B \-\-list \-\-all
List all open network connections (not just LISTEN).
.TP
.B \-h, \-\-help
Show help message and exit.
.TP
.B \-v, \-\-version
Show version information and exit.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Show process on port 3000:
.B portcheck 3000
.TP
Kill process on port 8080 with confirmation:
.B portcheck 8080 \-\-kill
.TP
Kill process on port 5432 immediately:
.B portcheck 5432 \-k
.TP
List all listening ports:
.B portcheck \-\-list
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
Error occurred (port not found, kill failed, invalid argument, etc.).
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR lsof (1),
.BR kill (1),
.BR ms (1)
